<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="130" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/334</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Cork</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Frost</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cork</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps">Queenstown</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-12">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1917</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 13, 1.25
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>British tanker <hi rend="italic">Saxonian</hi> left Newport News,
                                January 25 for Queenstown, crew 38, three Americans, no gun, no
                                wireless. Shelled 5.15 p.m., February 7, 280 miles southwest
                                Fastnet. No attempt escape. When 32 shells failed, submarine
                                torpedoed <hi rend="italic">Saxonian</hi> about <pb facs="0302" n="130" xml:id="pg_130"/> 6 p.m., sinking her. Then approached
                                crew in two open boats and asked vessel’s nationality, no offer
                                assistance. Weather: heavy swells, fresh southeast wind, darkness.
                                One boat picked up after 68 hours, other also, time unknown. When
                                other boat’s crew lands to-morrow morning can say if any Americans
                                lost. One saved in crew already landed. This telegram sent
                                Ambassador, Consul General.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_FW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frost</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>